<p><span style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 26px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">What Is Sattvic Diet?</span><br /></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 22px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Food, as all know, is fuel. Our ancient Ayurvedic texts explain this, and food is recognised as the source of all energy. Based on the energy food provides, the different kinds of foods are categorised as Tamasic, Rajasic and Sattvic.</span><br /></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 22px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each group has a certain value (known as Guna), and induces certain kinds of feelings and energy in the body. 
</span><br /></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 22px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A Sattvic diet derives its name from the Sanskrit word sattva which means pure.</span><br /></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 22px;"><span style="font-size: 26px; color: rgb(255, 255, 0);">"Eating a Sattvic diet can help an individual attain a calm mind, active body and live a long life."</span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Sattvic foods are light, fresh foods that are easily digestible. Fruits, vegetables, grains, spices and nuts, along with ethically-sourced dairy, are part of a Sattvic diet.</span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">The food should not be too spicy or pungent and should be consumed at normal to room temperature.</span> <br /></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 22px;"><br /></span></p>
<div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 80%;" src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Rajasic comes from the word rajas which means passion or activity. These foods are moderate - neither overly beneficial or bad for the body.
</span><br /></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Hot, salty, spicy and pungent foods that can give the system an emotional and physical boost come under this category. Stimulants like tea, coffee, pepper etc are rajasic. </span><br /></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Tamasic food is derived from the word tamas which means darkness in Sanskrit. These foods are said to be heavy on the digestive system and have negative effects on our mind, body and soul.</span><br /></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Tamasic food is derived from the word tamas which means darkness in Sanskrit. These foods are said to be heavy on the digestive system and have negative effects on our mind, body and soul.</span><br /></p>
<p><br /></p>
<div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 80%;" src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 26px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">What Does Sattvic Diet Bring?</span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">According to ancient food wisdom, a Sattvic diet brings a lot of benefits for mental and physical well-being. It is said to improve mental health and energy, and take the individual to a higher state of consciousness. </span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">It is also considered to have a balancing effect on the body and mind. Sattvic foods are said to be rich in prana or life force, since it consists of pure, whole and raw foods. It is not that difficult to follow a Sattvic diet plan.</span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">India boasts a wealth of delicious fruits and vegetables that can be prepared with minimal spice and oil, without compromising on flavour.</span><br /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 26px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">What Foods Can You Eat As Part Of A Sattvic Diet?</span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Here are the foods you can consume on a Sattvic diet food chart:&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">* </span><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">Grains: Rice, wheat, oats&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp; * </span><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">Legumes: Various kinds of pulses like moong dal, green gram etc</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp; *</span><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp;Fresh vegetables: Spinach, green beans, lauki, ash gourd, zucchini, steamed vegetables that are lightly spiced</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp;* Fresh fruits: Bananas, apples, oranges, pomegranate, grapes etc&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;* Nuts: Raw or lightly toasted nuts and seeds&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp; * Dairy: Fresh buttermilk, fresh curd, butter, ghee, fresh milk</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp; * Oils: Coconut oil, olive oil, sesame oil&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">&nbsp; &nbsp; * Spices: Ginger, cinnamon, cardamom, fennel (saunf), coriander, turmeric&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(51, 153, 102);">* Sweeteners: Jaggery, raw sugar, honey</span></p>
<div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 80%;" src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 26px; color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Sattvic Diet For Weight Loss: Is It Feasible?</span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Another benefit of eating a Sattvic diet is that it manages weight loss naturally, because you are more aware of what you eat and are eating foods in their whole, natural and unprocessed form. </span><br /></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 22px;">Sattvic diet food preparation encourages limited use of oil and fat, and the aim is to eat more raw/lightly steamed fruits and vegetables. Portion control is also part of the Sattvic diet, suggesting that people stick to “hand-sized” portions, which means that if it can’t fit in your hand, it’s probably too much!</span><br /></p>
